<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between a simple and detailed invoice?", answer: "A simple invoice applies a single tax rate and discount to the entire invoice. A detailed invoice allows you to set individual tax rates, item codes, units of measurement, and discounts for each line item separately. This is essential for businesses that sell products with different VAT rates or offer item-specific promotions." },
  { question: "When should I use per-item tax rates instead of a single rate?", answer: "Use per-item tax rates when your products or services fall under different tax categories. For example, in many countries food items are taxed at a reduced rate while electronics are taxed at the standard rate. Professional services might be exempt from VAT entirely. Per-item tax rates ensure each line item is taxed correctly for accurate accounting and legal compliance." },
  { question: "What is an item code and why include it on invoices?", answer: "An item code (also called SKU, product code, or part number) is a unique identifier for each product or service. Including item codes on invoices helps both the seller and buyer match invoice line items to specific products in their inventory or accounting systems. It reduces errors, speeds up payment processing, and simplifies returns or disputes." },
  { question: "What units of measurement should I use on invoices?", answer: "Use standard abbreviations that your industry recognizes: pcs (pieces), hrs (hours), kg (kilograms), m (meters), L (liters), or units specific to your field. Be consistent across all invoices. The unit clarifies what the quantity represents and prevents misunderstandings about what was delivered and what is being charged." },
  { question: "Can I apply different discount types to different items?", answer: "Yes, this detailed invoice generator lets you set a percentage discount or flat amount discount on each line item individually. This is useful for volume discounts on specific products, promotional pricing on selected items, or negotiated rates for particular services while keeping other items at full price." }
]) %>

